<br>
<DIV class="poemtitle">Invisible</DIV><br>
<TABLE><TR><TD>
<br />
Riding the bus now, I've become invisible—<br>
a breath, a mist that anyone can see through,<br> 
almost as if it's something I'd aspired to <br />
as life became more strange, unlivable. <br />
<br />
Riding the bus now, I'm immune to glances.<br />
Men let me pass without remark. The curve<br />
of present tense slides past the glass. We swerve<br />
and it's behind us, with all of our lost chances.<br />
<br />
Riding the bus, I practice how to look <br />
transparent, empty, gone. My eyes are closed.<br />
My face is leather-bound. I am exposed, <br />
yet plainly hidden. I am a blank book. <br />
<br />
Across the aisle, the girl I used to be—<br />
bound for trouble, unaware of me. <br />
<br />
<br>

